—increase in marketing and distribution expenses grew by 84.9% of total OPEX…… Management of the Nigerian Breweries Plc (NB)has published its unaudited financials of Q2, 2022 through the trading floor of The Nigerian Exchange (NGX) to the investing community on Friday which was sighted on the NGX’s website by The Ameh News (TAN) yesterday. According to the report, the NB performance major indicators recorded a PBT of NGN5.13 billion in Q2 of 2022 as against NGN494.27 million in 2021 same period while PAT came in higher at NGN5.31 billion as against NGN133.37 million in 2021. According to the report the brew paid a NGN179.05 million tax credit in the period under review,   The Company revenue grew to 31.6% year on year of half of 2022 representing 31.0% in Q2-22. According to report the headline price increases instituted across NB’s product categories, particularly in the premium segment supported the topline growth. In addition, analysts believe that revenue would have benefitted from an increased volume outturn following the expansion activities at its Ama brewery and resilient demand from on-trade channels like hotels, bars, restaurants, clubs, etc., which account for c.64.0% of beer industry sales. However, on a quarter on quarter basis, revenue declined by 1.1%.  While gross margin came in higher at 41.3% in the six months of 2022, with 553bases points higher than the corresponding period of six months of 2021 which representing 43.3%, as revenue hit 31.6% year on year grew faster than Costs of goods sold jumped to 20.2% year on year. In addition, experts think that the continued growth in the high-margin premium segment driven by the Heineken brand has been positive for price/volume mix and provides evidence that premiumisation continues to yield positive results.  The NB performance also indicated that the OPEX (are the day-to-day expenses a company incurs to keep its business operational) increased by 42.0% year on year in six months of 2022, resulting in an operating expense ratio (OER) of 33.1% as against the same period of 2021 recorded 30.8%. In the same vein, the growth in OPEX was due to a 52.1% year on year, increase in marketing and distribution expenses by 84.9% of total OPEX, reflecting the brewer’s continuous focus on increasing brand visibility.  Nonetheless, EBIT and EBITDA increased by 123.5% year on year and 41.8% year on year to NGN12.33 billion and NGN21.75 billion, respectively. Sequentially, EBIT showed a growth of 381bps while EBITDA showed 115bps margins improved to 9.0% as against 2021 which recorded 5.2% and 16.0% as against 2021 with 14.8% in period respectively.  Elsewhere, net finance charges grew by 43.4% year on year, due to a 106.2% year on year surge in the company FX losses due to exposure from its foreign currency denominated payables, amid a higher finance income hit 141.8% higher year on year.  The standalone report showed EPS recorded NGN0.01 increase to closed at NGN0.64 as against NGN2.32 recorded NGN0.96. Further analysis revealed that the EPS growth was supported by the sturdy topline growth to 31.0% year on year recorded in the reporting period.  Comment on the performance:  Analysts at Cordros Research said “they are impressed with NB’s ability to deliver growth in its top and bottom lines despite the prevailing constraints from FX illiquidity and elevated inflation existent in the operating environment. Overall, we believe NB remains on track to deliver positive earnings in 2022Full Year underpinned by a favourable price/volume mix and continuous improvements in its premiumisation strategy.”